            <p>Philadelphia Tebeth 2nd 5647<lb/>
                December 29th 1886<lb/></p>
            <p>Joseph Blumenthal&#44; Esquire President<lb/>
                of the Jewish Theological Seminary Association.<lb/></p>
            <p>My dear Sir&#58;<lb/></p>
            <p>Your letter&#44; in which I am officially informed<lb/> of the choice made by the Board of Trustees&#44; was unaccountably delayed<lb/> at our Post office.<lb/></p>
            <p>I now acknowledge its receipt&#44; and beg leave to say<lb/> in writing what I stated verbally the last time I had the pleasure of<lb/> our interview.  An honorable but most responsible position has been<lb/> given me by yourself and colleagues.  Various reasons combine in render&#45;<lb/>ing the performance of duties attending it very difficult&#44; notably my<lb/> residence in Philadelphia and my calling&#44; still I accept it thankfully<lb/> for the present&#44; believing that to do so is to benefit a sacred object.<lb/></p>
            <p>I appreciate the very kind and flattering manner<lb/> in which you were pleased to address me&#44; and I trust that&#44; under God&#44; my<lb/> future course will justify your expectations.  By the joint efforts of<lb/> all who are interested in our far reaching undertaking&#44; the Jewish<lb/> Theological Seminary will <sic>strengten</sic> conservatism&#44; and glorify Israel&#39;s<lb/> God in free America.<lb/></p>
            <p>Yours very faithfully&#44;<lb/>
                S. MORAIS<lb/></p>
            </body>
    </text>
